<BaseLayout title="The Pattern Child" description="The second story doorway after Lina.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Read</p>
    <h1>The Pattern Child</h1>
    <p class="lede">After Lina’s first story path, another child begins to notice a different kind of trouble: familiar patterns that have changed.</p>
    <p>The Pattern Child notices rhythm, repetition, imbalance, sequence, and fairness. They pay attention when a route, promise, count, trade, or habit no longer behaves in the way people remember.</p>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Second doorway</p>
      <h2>A different way of noticing</h2>
      <p>Lina notices what is quiet, hidden, or asking to be heard. The Pattern Child notices what repeats, breaks, tilts, or falls out of sequence.</p>
      <p>This matters in a world of crossings, routes, songs, symbols, counting stones, shared customs, and old rules that no longer feel fair.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Human centre</p>
      <h2>Who the Pattern Child is</h2>
      <p>The Pattern Child is not a machine-like puzzle solver. They are careful, curious, and quietly intense. They watch how things repeat: footsteps, trade habits, counting songs, routes, family customs, promises, and the way people take turns.</p>
      <p>When something feels wrong, they look for the part of the pattern that has changed. Other people move on quickly. The Pattern Child keeps seeing the small shift that matters.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Relationship</p>
      <h2>Lina and the Pattern Child</h2>
      <p>Lina can slow the moment down. The Pattern Child can show where the pattern has changed. Together, they notice both the feeling of a crossing and the shape of what is happening around it.</p>
      <p>They do not always move at the same pace. Lina needs space to listen before deciding. The Pattern Child wants to test the pattern before it shifts again.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">First pressure</p>
      <h2>The altered crossing</h2>
      <p>The Pattern Child’s first pressure begins near a crossing: a route, bridge, pass, or threshold that has changed its behaviour.</p>
      <p>The change is physical and visible. The crossing opens only every third attempt, tilts slightly to one side, hums in the wrong rhythm, moves its marker stones, or sends travellers back to the same starting point.</p>
      <p>The risk is practical before it is magical. People choose the wrong time to cross, trust an old rule that no longer works, or blame each other before they understand what has shifted.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Reader thread</p>
      <h2>What the Pattern Child helps readers see</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Rim</strong> — routes, repeated crossings, and movement.</li>
        <li><strong>Rimaeri</strong> — fairness, exchange, rhythm, and shared order.</li>
        <li><strong>Language</strong> — sound-patterns, naming, counting, and sequence.</li>
        <li><strong>Artefacts</strong> — tally marks, route cords, patterned cloth, counting stones, and measured paths.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>

